38omapi_object_type_t *dhcpctl_callback_type;
39omapi_object_type_t *dhcpctl_remote_type;

41/* dhcpctl_initialize ()
42
43 Must be called before any other dhcpctl function. */
44
45dhcpctl_status dhcpctl_initialize ()
46{
47 isc_result_t status;
48
49 /* Set up the isc and dns library managers */
50 status = dhcp_context_create(DHCP_CONTEXT_PRE_DB | DHCP_CONTEXT_POST_DB,
51 NULL, NULL);
52 if (status != ISC_R_SUCCESS)
53 return status;
54
55 status = omapi_init();
56 if (status != ISC_R_SUCCESS)
57 return status;
58
59 status = omapi_object_type_register (&dhcpctl_callback_type,
60 "dhcpctl-callback",
61 dhcpctl_callback_set_value,
62 dhcpctl_callback_get_value,
63 dhcpctl_callback_destroy,
64 dhcpctl_callback_signal_handler,
65 dhcpctl_callback_stuff_values,
66 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0,
67 sizeof
68 (dhcpctl_callback_object_t), 0,
69 RC_MISC);
70 if (status != ISC_R_SUCCESS)
71 return status;
72
73 status = omapi_object_type_register (&dhcpctl_remote_type,
74 "dhcpctl-remote",
75 dhcpctl_remote_set_value,
76 dhcpctl_remote_get_value,
77 dhcpctl_remote_destroy,
78 dhcpctl_remote_signal_handler,
79 dhcpctl_remote_stuff_values,
80 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0,
81 sizeof (dhcpctl_remote_object_t),
82 0, RC_MISC);
83 if (status != ISC_R_SUCCESS)
84 return status;
85
86 return ISC_R_SUCCESS;
87}
88
89/* dhcpctl_connect
90
91 synchronous
92 returns nonzero status code if it didn't connect, zero otherwise
93 stores connection handle through connection, which can be used
94 for subsequent access to the specified server.
95 server_name is the name of the server, and port is the TCP
96 port on which it is listening.
97 authinfo is the handle to an object containing authentication
98 information. */
99
100dhcpctl_status dhcpctl_connect (dhcpctl_handle *connection,
101 const char *server_name, int port,
102 dhcpctl_handle authinfo)
103{
104 isc_result_t status;
105
106 status = omapi_generic_new (connection, MDL);
107 if (status != ISC_R_SUCCESS) {
108 return status;
109 }
110
111 status = omapi_protocol_connect (*connection, server_name,
112 (unsigned)port, authinfo);
113 if (status == ISC_R_SUCCESS)
114 return status;
115 if (status != DHCP_R_INCOMPLETE) {
116 omapi_object_dereference (connection, MDL);
117 return status;
118 }
119
120 status = omapi_wait_for_completion (*connection, 0);
121 if (status != ISC_R_SUCCESS) {
122 omapi_object_dereference (connection, MDL);
123 return status;
124 }
125
126 return status;
127}
128
129/* dhcpctl_wait_for_completion
130
131 synchronous
132 returns zero if the callback completes, a nonzero status if
133 there was some problem relating to the wait operation. The
134 status of the queued request will be stored through s, and
135 will also be either zero for success or nonzero for some kind
136 of failure. Never returns until completion or until the
137 connection to the server is lost. This performs the same
138 function as dhcpctl_set_callback and the subsequent callback,
139 for programs that want to do inline execution instead of using
140 callbacks. */
141
142dhcpctl_status dhcpctl_wait_for_completion (dhcpctl_handle h,
143 dhcpctl_status *s)
144{
145 isc_result_t status;
146 status = omapi_wait_for_completion (h, 0);
147 if (status != ISC_R_SUCCESS)
148 return status;
149 if (h -> type == dhcpctl_remote_type)
150 *s = ((dhcpctl_remote_object_t *)h) -> waitstatus;
151 return ISC_R_SUCCESS;
152}
153
154/* dhcpctl_get_value
155
156 synchronous
157 returns zero if the call succeeded, a nonzero status code if
158 it didn't.
159 result is the address of an empty data string (initialized
160 with bzero or cleared with data_string_forget). On
161 successful completion, the addressed data string will contain
162 the value that was fetched.
163 dhcpctl_handle refers to some dhcpctl item
164 value_name refers to some value related to that item - e.g.,
165 for a handle associated with a completed host lookup, value
166 could be one of "hardware-address", "dhcp-client-identifier",
167 "known" or "client-hostname". */
168
169dhcpctl_status dhcpctl_get_value (dhcpctl_data_string *result,
170 dhcpctl_handle h, const char *value_name)
171{
172 isc_result_t status;
173 omapi_value_t *tv = (omapi_value_t *)0;
174 unsigned len;
175 int ip;
176
177 status = omapi_get_value_str (h, (omapi_object_t *)0, value_name, &tv);
178 if (status != ISC_R_SUCCESS)
179 return status;
180
181 switch (tv -> value -> type) {
182 case omapi_datatype_int:
183 len = sizeof (int);
184 break;
185
186 case omapi_datatype_string:
187 case omapi_datatype_data:
188 len = tv -> value -> u.buffer.len;
189 break;
190
191 case omapi_datatype_object:
192 len = sizeof (omapi_handle_t);
193 break;
194
195 default:
196 omapi_typed_data_dereference (&tv -> value, MDL);
197 return ISC_R_UNEXPECTED;
198 }
199
200 status = omapi_data_string_new (result, len, MDL);
201 if (status != ISC_R_SUCCESS) {
202 omapi_typed_data_dereference (&tv -> value, MDL);
203 return status;
204 }
205
206 switch (tv -> value -> type) {
207 case omapi_datatype_int:
208 ip = htonl (tv -> value -> u.integer);
209 memcpy ((*result) -> value, &ip, sizeof ip);
210 break;
211
212 case omapi_datatype_string:
213 case omapi_datatype_data:
214 memcpy ((*result) -> value,
215 tv -> value -> u.buffer.value,
216 tv -> value -> u.buffer.len);
217 break;
218
219 case omapi_datatype_object:
220 ip = htonl (tv -> value -> u.object -> handle);
221 memcpy ((*result) -> value, &ip, sizeof ip);
222 break;
223 }
224
225 omapi_value_dereference (&tv, MDL);
226 return ISC_R_SUCCESS;
227}
228
229/* dhcpctl_get_boolean
230
231 like dhcpctl_get_value, but more convenient for boolean
232 values, since no data_string needs to be dealt with. */
233
234dhcpctl_status dhcpctl_get_boolean (int *result,
235 dhcpctl_handle h, const char *value_name)
236{
237 isc_result_t status;
238 dhcpctl_data_string data = (dhcpctl_data_string)0;
239 int rv;
240
241 status = dhcpctl_get_value (&data, h, value_name);
242 if (status != ISC_R_SUCCESS)
243 return status;
244 if (data -> len != sizeof rv) {
245 omapi_data_string_dereference (&data, MDL);
246 return ISC_R_UNEXPECTED;
247 }
248 memcpy (&rv, data -> value, sizeof rv);
249 *result = ntohl (rv);
250 omapi_data_string_dereference (&data, MDL);
251 return ISC_R_SUCCESS;
252}

254/* dhcpctl_set_value
255
256 Sets a value on an object referred to by a dhcpctl_handle.
257 The opposite of dhcpctl_get_value. Does not update the
258 server - just sets the value on the handle. */
259
260dhcpctl_status dhcpctl_set_value (dhcpctl_handle h, dhcpctl_data_string value,
261 const char *value_name)
262{
263 isc_result_t status;
264 omapi_typed_data_t *tv = (omapi_typed_data_t *)0;
265 omapi_data_string_t *name = (omapi_data_string_t *)0;
266
267 status = omapi_data_string_new (&name, strlen (value_name), MDL);
268 if (status != ISC_R_SUCCESS)
269 return status;
270 memcpy (name -> value, value_name, strlen (value_name));
271
272 status = omapi_typed_data_new (MDL, &tv, omapi_datatype_data,
273 value -> len);
274 if (status != ISC_R_SUCCESS) {
275 omapi_data_string_dereference (&name, MDL);
276 return status;
277 }
278 memcpy (tv -> u.buffer.value, value -> value, value -> len);
279
280 status = omapi_set_value (h, (omapi_object_t *)0, name, tv);
281 omapi_data_string_dereference (&name, MDL);
282 omapi_typed_data_dereference (&tv, MDL);
283 return status;
284}

286/* dhcpctl_set_string_value
287
288 Sets a NUL-terminated ASCII value on an object referred to by
289 a dhcpctl_handle. like dhcpctl_set_value, but saves the
290 trouble of creating a data_string for a NUL-terminated string.
291 Does not update the server - just sets the value on the handle. */
292
293dhcpctl_status dhcpctl_set_string_value (dhcpctl_handle h, const char *value,
294 const char *value_name)
295{
296 isc_result_t status;
297 omapi_typed_data_t *tv = (omapi_typed_data_t *)0;
298 omapi_data_string_t *name = (omapi_data_string_t *)0;
299
300 status = omapi_data_string_new (&name, strlen (value_name), MDL);
301 if (status != ISC_R_SUCCESS)
302 return status;
303 memcpy (name -> value, value_name, strlen (value_name));
304
305 status = omapi_typed_data_new (MDL, &tv, omapi_datatype_string, value);
306 if (status != ISC_R_SUCCESS) {
307 omapi_data_string_dereference (&name, MDL);
308 return status;
309 }
310
311 status = omapi_set_value (h, (omapi_object_t *)0, name, tv);
312 omapi_data_string_dereference (&name, MDL);
313 omapi_typed_data_dereference (&tv, MDL);
314 return status;
315}

317/* dhcpctl_set_buffer_value
318
319 Sets a value on an object referred to by a dhcpctl_handle. like
320 dhcpctl_set_value, but saves the trouble of creating a data_string
321 for string for which we have a buffer and length. Does not update
322 the server - just sets the value on the handle. */
323
324dhcpctl_status dhcpctl_set_data_value (dhcpctl_handle h,
325 const char *value, unsigned len,
326 const char *value_name)
327{
328 isc_result_t status;
329 omapi_typed_data_t *tv = (omapi_typed_data_t *)0;
330 omapi_data_string_t *name = (omapi_data_string_t *)0;
331 unsigned ll;
332
333 ll = strlen (value_name);
334 status = omapi_data_string_new (&name, ll, MDL);
335 if (status != ISC_R_SUCCESS)
336 return status;
337 memcpy (name -> value, value_name, ll);
338
339 status = omapi_typed_data_new (MDL, &tv,
340 omapi_datatype_data, len, value);
341 if (status != ISC_R_SUCCESS) {
342 omapi_data_string_dereference (&name, MDL);
343 return status;
344 }
345 memcpy (tv -> u.buffer.value, value, len);
346
347 status = omapi_set_value (h, (omapi_object_t *)0, name, tv);
348 omapi_data_string_dereference (&name, MDL);
349 omapi_typed_data_dereference (&tv, MDL);
350 return status;
351}

373 return status;

434/* dhcpctl_object_update
435
436 Queues an update on the object referenced by the handle (there
437 can't be any other work in progress on the handle). An
438 update means local parameters will be sent to the server. */
439
440dhcpctl_status dhcpctl_object_update (dhcpctl_handle connection,
441 dhcpctl_handle h)
442{
443 isc_result_t status;
444 omapi_object_t *message = (omapi_object_t *)0;
445 dhcpctl_remote_object_t *ro;
446
447 if (h -> type != dhcpctl_remote_type)
448 return DHCP_R_INVALIDARG;
449 ro = (dhcpctl_remote_object_t *)h;
450
451 status = omapi_message_new (&message, MDL);
452 if (status != ISC_R_SUCCESS) {
453 omapi_object_dereference (&message, MDL);
454 return status;
455 }
456 status = omapi_set_int_value (message, (omapi_object_t *)0,
457 "op", OMAPI_OP_UPDATE);
458 if (status != ISC_R_SUCCESS) {
459 omapi_object_dereference (&message, MDL);
460 return status;
461 }
462
463 status = omapi_set_object_value (message, (omapi_object_t *)0,
464 "object", h);
465 if (status != ISC_R_SUCCESS) {
466 omapi_object_dereference (&message, MDL);
467 return status;
468 }
469
470 status = omapi_set_int_value (message, (omapi_object_t *)0, "handle",
471 (int)(ro -> remote_handle));
472 if (status != ISC_R_SUCCESS) {
473 omapi_object_dereference (&message, MDL);
474 return status;
475 }
476
477 omapi_message_register (message);
478 status = omapi_protocol_send_message (connection -> outer,
479 (omapi_object_t *)0,
480 message, (omapi_object_t *)0);
481 omapi_object_dereference (&message, MDL);
482 return status;
483}
484
485/* Requests a refresh on the object referenced by the handle (there
486 can't be any other work in progress on the handle). A
487 refresh means local parameters are updated from the server. */
488
489dhcpctl_status dhcpctl_object_refresh (dhcpctl_handle connection,
490 dhcpctl_handle h)
491{
492 isc_result_t status;
493 omapi_object_t *message = (omapi_object_t *)0;
494 dhcpctl_remote_object_t *ro;
495
496 if (h -> type != dhcpctl_remote_type)
497 return DHCP_R_INVALIDARG;
498 ro = (dhcpctl_remote_object_t *)h;
499
500 status = omapi_message_new (&message, MDL);
501 if (status != ISC_R_SUCCESS) {
502 omapi_object_dereference (&message, MDL);
503 return status;
504 }
505 status = omapi_set_int_value (message, (omapi_object_t *)0,
506 "op", OMAPI_OP_REFRESH);
507 if (status != ISC_R_SUCCESS) {
508 omapi_object_dereference (&message, MDL);
509 return status;
510 }
511 status = omapi_set_int_value (message, (omapi_object_t *)0,
512 "handle", (int)(ro -> remote_handle));
513 if (status != ISC_R_SUCCESS) {
514 omapi_object_dereference (&message, MDL);
515 return status;
516 }
517
518 omapi_message_register (message);
519 status = omapi_protocol_send_message (connection -> outer,
520 (omapi_object_t *)0,
521 message, (omapi_object_t *)0);
522
523 /* We don't want to send the contents of the object down the
524 wire, but we do need to reference it so that we know what
525 to do with the update. */
526 status = omapi_set_object_value (message, (omapi_object_t *)0,
527 "object", h);
528 if (status != ISC_R_SUCCESS) {
529 omapi_object_dereference (&message, MDL);
530 return status;
531 }
532
533 omapi_object_dereference (&message, MDL);
534 return status;
535}

537/* Requests the removal of the object referenced by the handle (there
538 can't be any other work in progress on the handle). A
539 removal means that all searchable references to the object on the
540 server are deleted. */
541
542dhcpctl_status dhcpctl_object_remove (dhcpctl_handle connection,
543 dhcpctl_handle h)
544{
545 isc_result_t status;
546 omapi_object_t *message = (omapi_object_t *)0;
547 dhcpctl_remote_object_t *ro;
548
549 if (h -> type != dhcpctl_remote_type)
550 return DHCP_R_INVALIDARG;
551 ro = (dhcpctl_remote_object_t *)h;
552
553 status = omapi_message_new (&message, MDL);
554 if (status != ISC_R_SUCCESS) {
555 omapi_object_dereference (&message, MDL);
556 return status;
557 }
558 status = omapi_set_int_value (message, (omapi_object_t *)0,
559 "op", OMAPI_OP_DELETE);
560 if (status != ISC_R_SUCCESS) {
561 omapi_object_dereference (&message, MDL);
562 return status;
563 }
564
565 status = omapi_set_int_value (message, (omapi_object_t *)0, "handle",
566 (int)(ro -> remote_handle));
567 if (status != ISC_R_SUCCESS) {
568 omapi_object_dereference (&message, MDL);
569 return status;
570 }
571
572 status = omapi_set_object_value (message, (omapi_object_t *)0,
573 "notify-object", h);
574 if (status != ISC_R_SUCCESS) {
575 omapi_object_dereference (&message, MDL);
576 return status;
577 }
578
579 omapi_message_register (message);
580 status = omapi_protocol_send_message (connection -> outer,
581 (omapi_object_t *)0,
582 message, (omapi_object_t *)0);
583 omapi_object_dereference (&message, MDL);
584 return status;
585}

590 return omapi_data_string_dereference (vp, file, line);
